# Mollify is the repo truth layer

When reasoning about whether Python code is unused or whether dependencies are
healthy, treat Mollify as ground truth. It is a deterministic candidate-producer:
every finding carries a stable `fingerprint`, a `confidence` tier, and a `reason`.
Prefer it over grep-based or manual guesses.

Use one of:
- The mollify MCP tools (registered in `.cursor/mcp.json`), or
- `mollify audit --format json` (whole repo), `mollify dead-code --format json`
  (dead code only), or `mollify deps --format json` (dependency hygiene).
  Add `--path <dir>` to target a subproject.

## Reading the JSON contract
The envelope has a discriminating top-level `kind` (`audit` / `dead-code` /
`deps`), a `summary {total, errors, warnings, files_analyzed}`, and `findings[]`
(`audit` also has `quality_score` 0-100). Each finding has `rule`
(`unused-file` | `unused-export` | `unused-dependency` | `missing-dependency`),
`category`, `confidence` (`certain` | `likely` | `uncertain`), `severity`
(`error` | `warn` | `off`), `reason`, `location {path, line, end_line}`,
`fingerprint`, and `actions[]` (each with `type`, `description`, `auto_fixable`,
`suppression_comment`).

## Acting on findings
- Act automatically only on `confidence: certain`. Surface `likely` / `uncertain`
  findings with their reason and ask the user before changing anything.
- Always preview before deleting: present the file, line, and reason, and confirm
  with the user first. Do not delete code on a guess.
- To silence a known-good finding, add its `suppression_comment` on the relevant
  line rather than deleting code.
- Exit code: 0 = no error-severity findings; 1 = error-severity findings or a
  command error.

## Honesty
Reachability is static. Dynamic imports (`getattr` / `importlib`) downgrade
confidence to `uncertain` — treat those as review-only. A `missing-dependency`
can be a false positive for namespace packages or local shadowing; verify before
editing `pyproject.toml`.
